"""
MKT Context Commentary — Genesis chapters 27–28
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-genesis-27-28.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/genesis.json (prior chapters; merge_comm skips already-present entries)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch27: The deathbed blessing is legally irrevocable in the ANE — Isaac's "trembling violently" (v.33)
  reflects the legal reality: a spoken blessing once given cannot be recalled, even obtained by fraud
- Ch27:v36 yaʿăqōḇ wordplay: "does he not rightly bear the name Jacob?" — Esau connects the name
  to ʿāqaḇ (to supplant/seize by the heel); the pun is the same as in 25:26
- Ch27:vv.39-40 Esau's blessing: the Hebrew min can mean "from" (abundance FROM the earth) or
  "away from" (lack of the earth's richness); most translations follow the "away from" reading
  given the contrast with Jacob's blessing; both readings are grammatically possible
- Ch27:v46 / 28:1: Rebekah's "Hittite women" pretext — the stated reason differs from the
  actual reason (Esau's murder threat v.41); this is a social/diplomatic cover for a safety matter
- Ch28:v12 sullam (stairway): the Akkadian cognate simmiltu refers to a ziggurat ramp;
  the connection is debated but the imagery of a ramp between heaven and earth is consistent
  with ANE ziggurat theology
- Ch28:v18 massebah (pillar): standing stones as memorial markers predate the Mosaic prohibition
  (Lev 26:1; Deut 16:22); the narrator does not condemn Jacob's pillar
- Ch28:vv.20-22 conditional vow form: "if... then" is standard ANE vow structure; Jacob is not
  bargaining but expressing the conditional acceptance of covenant relationship
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

GENESIS = {
  "27": {
    "1": '<p>"When Isaac was old and his eyes were so weak that he could no longer see" — blindness in the ANE rendered a patriarch socially and legally vulnerable. A blind man could not witness transactions, verify identities, or exercise the normal functions of household authority except through speech and touch. The narrative uses this physical limitation as the mechanism for the deception, but it also heightens the pathos: Isaac is preparing for the most solemn act of his patriarchal life (the deathbed blessing) in a condition of total dependence on those around him. Deathbed blessings were performative speech acts with legal force — not mere expressions of goodwill.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"I am now an old man and don\'t know the day of my death" — the awareness of approaching death as the context for the blessing reflects ANE practice. Deathbed blessings and testamentary dispositions were standard legal procedures in the ancient Near East; Nuzi tablets and Mesopotamian legal documents from the second millennium document the formal transfer of inheritance rights through spoken blessing accompanied by witnesses. Isaac\'s urgency is not merely emotional but reflects the legal framework: the blessing must be given before death to be valid.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"Get your weapons — your quiver and bow — and go out to the open country to hunt some wild game for me" — the hunt before the blessing is not incidental. The meal that precedes a covenant or legal act in the ANE functioned as the covenant meal — the shared food sealed and ratified the transaction. Isaac\'s request for game (not domestic animals, which would be easier to obtain) signals the solemnity of the occasion: this is a special-occasion meal that marks the gravity of what is about to take place, not an ordinary dinner.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"Prepare me the kind of tasty food I like... so that I may give you my blessing before I die" — the sequence is significant: food first, then blessing. In ANE legal and covenantal contexts, the shared meal established the relational context in which an oath, covenant, or legal act was performed. The blessing itself was not merely a prayer or a wish; it was a spoken declaration that conferred specific rights, status, and covenant standing on the recipient. Isaac intends to formally transfer the Abrahamic covenant promises to Esau.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"Rebekah was listening as Isaac spoke to his son Esau" — the narrator positions Rebekah as a hidden witness, not an eavesdropper in the deceptive sense, but as someone who overhears a household conversation. In the ANE domestic context, the women\'s quarters and the main living spaces often overlapped in smaller households, and overhearing was not necessarily improper. Rebekah\'s knowledge of what Isaac intended puts her in direct conflict with the oracle she received before the twins\' birth (25:23): "the older will serve the younger."</p>',

    "6": '<p>"Rebekah said to her son Jacob, \'Look, I overheard your father say to your brother Esau\'" — Rebekah intervenes on the basis of the prenatal oracle she received (25:23). The narrative does not explicitly reference the oracle here, but the reader familiar with it understands that Rebekah is acting on a divine directive received at the beginning of the twins\' story. The tension between her knowledge of the oracle and her husband\'s intentions drives the deception. The moral complexity is intentional: the narrator presents Rebekah\'s intervention without editorial condemnation.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"In the presence of the LORD before I die" — Rebekah\'s report of Isaac\'s words adds a detail not present in the original speech: "in the presence of the LORD" (<em>lipnê YHWH</em>). Whether Isaac actually said this (and the narrator omitted it) or whether Rebekah is adding the religious weight to motivate Jacob, the phrase clarifies what is at stake: this is not merely a paternal preference but a covenantal act performed before YHWH. The blessing invokes divine backing and carries divine authority once spoken.</p>',

    "8": '<p>"Listen carefully and do what I tell you" — Rebekah\'s instruction to Jacob frames what follows as a commanded action, not a Jacob-initiated scheme. The narrative responsibility is deliberately distributed: Rebekah plans, Jacob executes (with initial hesitation). This distribution of agency is consistent with the ANE narrative convention of presenting complex moral situations without resolving the blame — multiple parties bear responsibility, and the reader must weigh the competing goods (covenant fidelity to the oracle vs. honesty to the patriarch).</p>',

    "9": '<p>"Go out to the flock and bring me two choice young goats" — domestic goats as a substitute for hunted game: Rebekah replicates the required meal using what she controls (the domestic flock) rather than what Esau would provide (wild game). The substitution depends on her culinary skill — she is confident she can prepare goat meat to taste indistinguishable from wild game. This confidence suggests either significant skill or the narrative assumption that Isaac\'s sense of taste is, like his sight, compromised by age.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"Take it to your father to eat, so that he may give you his blessing before he dies" — the goal is stated plainly: obtain the blessing for Jacob. Rebekah\'s plan is legally audacious because ANE deathbed blessings were irrevocable — once given, they could not be retracted. She is not merely seeking a paternal preference but a legal transfer that, once made, cannot be undone regardless of how it was obtained. This is confirmed in v.33, when Isaac acknowledges the blessing stands even after discovering the fraud.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"My brother Esau is a hairy man while I have smooth skin" — Jacob\'s objection is practical, not moral. He is not troubled by the ethics of deceiving his blind father but by the risk of detection. The contrast between Esau\'s hairiness and Jacob\'s smooth skin was established at birth (25:25 describes Esau as "covered with hair"). Jacob\'s concern is that the physical touch — the only sensory channel available to Isaac for verification — will expose the deception.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"I would appear to be tricking him and would bring down a curse on myself rather than a blessing" — Jacob\'s fear is of covenant retribution, not relational guilt. The word <em>mĕtaʿtēaʿ</em> (tricking, mocking) is the same verbal root used in 39:14 and 17 for "mocking" in the Joseph story. The curse/blessing dichotomy frames this as a covenant transaction with consequences in both directions: a successful blessing confers covenant standing; a failed deception could invert it. Jacob\'s calculus is risk-management, not ethics.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"My son, let the curse fall on me" — Rebekah\'s acceptance of potential curse-bearing is strikingly maternal and covenantally loaded. In the ANE, curse-transference — taking upon oneself the consequence of another\'s action — was understood within the framework of substitutionary responsibility. Rebekah assumes she is protected by the oracle (25:23) and by her confidence that the plan will succeed. The phrase echoes, distantly, the later concept of covenant representation: one person standing in for another in receiving or bearing covenant consequences.</p>',

    "14": '<p>"She prepared some tasty food, just the way his father liked it" — the narrator confirms Rebekah\'s culinary execution was successful. The phrase "just the way his father liked it" (<em>kattaʿam ʾăšer ʾāhēḇ ʾāḇîw</em>) uses the same vocabulary as Isaac\'s original request (v.4: "the tasty food I like"), signaling that the substitution was qualitatively convincing. The domestic goat preparation replicates what wild game would have provided.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"Rebekah took the best clothes of Esau her older son, which she had in the house" — that Rebekah had Esau\'s best clothes "in the house" indicates she had them under her keeping, perhaps stored in the women\'s quarters. In the ANE, a person\'s clothing carried their social identity and could even carry their personal presence — putting on another\'s garment was a recognized form of identity substitution in some contexts (cf. Tamar putting on a veil in ch.38). The smell of Esau\'s field-worn clothes (noted in v.27) will become the crucial sensory detail that convinces Isaac.</p>',

    "16": '<p>"She covered his hands and the smooth part of his neck with the goatskins" — the physical disguise targets the specific body areas Isaac is likely to touch to distinguish his sons. Goat kids were chosen (v.9) precisely because their skin has a texture similar to Esau\'s hairy skin when felt with aged, weakened hands. The precision of the disguise — covering hands and neck but not face — reflects a calculated understanding of how Isaac would conduct his verification: by touch, not sight.</p>',

    "17": '<p>"Then she handed to her son Jacob the tasty food and the bread she had made" — the bread included alongside the meat reflects the full meal expected for a covenantal occasion. The complete meal package (meat prepared to taste, bread for the table) matches what Isaac requested. Rebekah\'s thoroughness ensures the sensory experience of the meal will match expectation even if the physical touch fails to expose the substitution.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"He went to his father and said, \'My father.\' \'Yes, my son,\' he answered. \'Who is it?\'" — Isaac\'s immediate question "Who is it?" (<em>mî ʾāttāh</em>) signals his uncertainty even before any physical contact. The blind patriarch is relying on voice as his primary means of identification, and Jacob\'s voice will be the weak point in the deception (v.22: "the voice is the voice of Jacob"). The opening exchange establishes the sensory battleground of the scene: Isaac\'s faculties are impaired but not absent.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"I am Esau your firstborn" — Jacob\'s explicit lie directly invokes covenant category: <em>bĕkhōrĕkhā</em> (your firstborn). The firstborn status conferred specific legal rights: the double share of inheritance and the headship of the household after the patriarch\'s death. By claiming to be Esau the firstborn, Jacob is asserting the specific legal standing that the blessing is designed to confer. "I have done what you asked" — the deception is comprehensive: identity, action, and status are all falsely claimed.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"The LORD your God gave me success" — Jacob invokes YHWH in his deception — the most theologically disturbing moment in the chapter. Using divine agency as a cover story for the fraud is a form of false witness. Yet the narrative also works on a second level: YHWH has, in fact, been working toward exactly this outcome (the oracle of 25:23); Jacob\'s lie contains an inadvertent truth. The narrator does not resolve the irony — the statement is both a lie and, from a providential perspective, accurate.</p>',

    "21": '<p>"Come near so I can touch you, my son, to know whether you really are my son Esau or not" — Isaac\'s request for tactile verification reflects the blind man\'s dependence on touch as the most reliable sensory channel available to him. The scene now turns on whether the goatskin disguise will hold up to direct physical examination. Isaac is not passive; he is actively trying to verify identity, which makes the deception more psychologically tense and the eventual success more remarkable.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"The voice is the voice of Jacob, but the hands are the hands of Esau" — Isaac\'s diagnostic observation is the central line of the chapter. He has correctly identified the anomaly — the voice profile does not match the tactile profile — but he allows the physical evidence to override the auditory. In the ANE context, voice identification was not necessarily considered more reliable than touch; each sense had its domain. The narrative may also be suggesting that Isaac wants to believe it is Esau, and so allows the evidence he prefers to prevail.</p>',

    "23": '<p>"He did not recognize him, for his hands were hairy like those of his brother Esau; so he proceeded to bless him" — the narrator\'s explanation ("for his hands were hairy like those of his brother Esau") confirms that the goatskin disguise successfully deceived the tactile examination. The phrase "he proceeded to bless him" (<em>waybārăkehû</em>) — the imperfect of immediate consequence — signals that the blessing followed directly and without further hesitation once the physical test was passed.</p>',

    "24": '<p>"Are you really my son Esau?" — Isaac\'s final verbal challenge suggests lingering doubt even after the physical test. The voice has raised suspicion that the hands could not fully settle. Jacob\'s simple "I am" (<em>ʾānî</em>) is the last verbal step in the deception. The brevity of the lie — a single word — mirrors the gravity of the act: one word now seals a covenant transaction that cannot be undone.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"Jacob brought it to him and he ate; and he brought some wine and he drank" — the shared meal is now complete. In ANE covenantal and legal contexts, the shared meal between principal parties ratified and sealed the transaction. By eating the food Jacob prepared and drinking the wine he offered, Isaac has completed the covenant-meal dimension of the blessing ceremony. The meal\'s completion makes the subsequent blessing not merely a spoken wish but a covenant act sealed by shared table.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"Come here, my son, and kiss me" — the physical embrace before the spoken blessing adds another dimension to the ceremony. A kiss between patriarch and heir was a social and sometimes legal gesture of recognition and affirmation. The request for Jacob to come close for the kiss also allows Isaac one more sensory check: the smell of the garments. The smell will become decisive in v.27 — not because it is a more reliable identifier than voice, but because it triggers the blessing speech.</p>',

    "27": '<p>"When Isaac caught the smell of his clothes, he blessed him" — the smell of field and outdoor work embedded in Esau\'s garments triggers Isaac\'s blessing. The olfactory dimension is significant: in the ANE, smell was associated with divine presence (incense, sacrifices ascending to God); the smell of a field "that the LORD has blessed" collapses the distinction between the garment and the land of promise. Isaac\'s blessing is now in full flight, triggered by a sensory cue that belongs to Esau but is worn by Jacob.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"May God give you heaven\'s dew and earth\'s richness — an abundance of grain and new wine" — the agricultural blessing is framed in the cosmic dimensions of the ANE: dew (<em>ṭal</em>) as the gift of heaven above, the produce of the earth below. In the arid Levantine context, dew was a critical supplement to rainfall for crops; it was understood as a divine gift (cf. Hos 14:5; Zech 8:12). Grain (<em>dāgān</em>) and new wine (<em>tîrôš</em>) are the primary agricultural commodities of the ancient Near East, representing economic prosperity and social stability.</p>',

    "29": '<p>"May nations serve you and peoples bow down to you. Be lord over your brothers, and may the sons of your mother bow down to you" — the blessing\'s second dimension is political sovereignty: international dominance and family headship. "Be lord (<em>gĕḇîr</em>) over your brothers" uses the term for a master or overlord — not merely elder sibling priority but actual authority. The curse/blessing formula at the end ("may those who curse you be cursed and those who bless you be blessed") is identical to the Abrahamic covenant language of 12:3, confirming that Isaac is transferring the full covenant standing to the recipient of this blessing.</p>',

    "30": '<p>"Jacob had scarcely left his father\'s presence, his brother Esau came in from hunting" — the dramatic timing — Jacob barely out the door as Esau arrives — is a literary construction that heightens the story\'s tension while reflecting the ANE narrative convention of near-collision that reveals divine timing. The proximity of the two events underscores how narrowly the deception succeeded and how precisely the outcome was arranged.</p>',

    "31": '<p>"He too prepared some tasty food and brought it to his father" — Esau\'s action mirrors the setup of the chapter: he fulfills his father\'s request exactly as commanded. The reader now experiences the scene from Esau\'s perspective, which is one of complete innocence and filial duty. The narrative\'s sympathetic presentation of Esau at this point (he hunted, he prepared, he brought) makes the subsequent revelation all the more devastating.</p>',

    "32": '<p>"Who are you?" — Isaac\'s question is now asked with full visual blindness and (presumably) the assumption that the blessing is complete. Esau\'s self-identification — "I am your son, your firstborn, Esau" — uses the exact three-part formula that Jacob falsely claimed in v.19. The parallel construction (your son / your firstborn / Esau) now produces a collision of identities that Isaac must process without any way to resolve it physically.</p>',

    "33": '<p>"Isaac trembled violently" — <em>wayyeḥĕrad Yiṣḥāq ḥărādāh gĕḏōlāh ʿad-mĕʾōḏ</em> (Isaac trembled a great trembling very greatly) — the triple intensification signals a response of shock and perhaps divine awe. Isaac understands immediately what has happened and, more importantly, understands that it cannot be undone. "Indeed he will be blessed!" (<em>wĕgam-bārûkh yihyeh</em>) — Isaac\'s acknowledgment that the blessing stands despite the fraud is the chapter\'s theological crux. In ANE legal culture, a deathbed blessing once spoken before witnesses (even if that witness was only YHWH) was binding. The fraud did not invalidate the legal act.</p>',

    "34": '<p>"He burst out with a loud and bitter cry" — <em>ṣĕʿāqāh gĕḏōlāh ûmārāh ʿad-mĕʾōḏ</em> (a great and exceedingly bitter cry). Esau\'s grief is presented without reservation. The vocabulary of "loud and bitter cry" is used elsewhere in the OT for the cry of the oppressed (Exod 11:6; Est 4:1). The narrative invites sympathy for Esau even while maintaining that the oracle (25:23) is being fulfilled. The reader holds both truths simultaneously: the covenant trajectory was divinely ordered, and Esau\'s pain is genuine and legitimate.</p>',

    "35": '<p>"Your brother came deceitfully and took your blessing" — Isaac\'s statement is the first explicit moral verdict from within the narrative: Jacob came <em>bĕmirmāh</em> (by deceit, by treachery). The word <em>mirmāh</em> is the OT\'s clearest term for fraud and deceptive dealing (cf. Ps 55:11; Prov 12:20). Isaac does not mitigate what happened. Yet his verdict has no power to reverse the legal reality — the blessing stands.</p>',

    "36": '<p>"Isn\'t he rightly named Jacob? This is the second time he has taken advantage of me" — Esau\'s wordplay on Jacob\'s name connects the name to the verb <em>ʿāqaḇ</em> (to supplant, to seize by the heel; cf. 25:26). "He has taken advantage of me" uses the same verb: <em>wayyaʿqĕḇēnî</em>. The birthright incident (25:33) is the first; this is the second. Esau\'s analysis is accurate: the name Jacob (yaʿăqōḇ) has twice proven prophetic of the character. The pun is the narrative\'s way of signaling that these events are patterned, not accidental.</p>',

    "37": '<p>"I have made him lord over you and have made all his relatives his servants, and I have sustained him with grain and new wine" — Isaac recites what has already been given in the blessing: the political sovereignty (lord/gĕḇîr) and the agricultural wealth (grain and wine). His rhetorical question — "So what can I possibly do for you, my son?" — is genuinely an acknowledgment that he has nothing left to give in the same covenantal register. The covenant promises have been fully transferred.</p>',

    "38": '<p>"Do you have only one blessing, my father?" — Esau\'s question reflects a misunderstanding or a desperate hope: perhaps the patriarch has a second covenant-level blessing in reserve. The ANE reality was that a patriarch could make multiple bequests, but the foundational covenant blessing — the one that carried the divine promises of land, descendants, and the Abrahamic covenant — was singular and had been transferred. Esau\'s weeping is the narrative\'s final sympathetic portrait of him before his murderous resolve (v.41).</p>',

    "39": '<p>"Your dwelling will be away from the earth\'s richness, away from the dew of heaven above" — Esau\'s counter-blessing opens with the negative inversion of Jacob\'s agricultural abundance. The Hebrew <em>miššmannê hāʾāreṣ</em> uses the same preposition (<em>min</em>) as Jacob\'s blessing, but in the privative sense: "away from" rather than "from" (abundance). The contrast is structured to be heard against Jacob\'s blessing in v.28 — everything Jacob received in the positive, Esau receives in the negative. Edom\'s arid territory (the highlands of modern Jordan/southern Israel) is the geographical reality behind the poetic image.</p>',

    "40": '<p>"You will live by the sword and you will serve your brother. But when you grow restless, you will throw his yoke from off your neck" — Esau\'s blessing contains both subjection and a future release clause. "Live by the sword" reflects the warrior lifestyle of the Edomites, attested in later history. "Serve your brother" echoes 25:23 (the oracle at birth). The release clause — "when you grow restless, you will throw his yoke from off your neck" — is fulfilled in the Edomite revolt against Israelite domination (2 Kgs 8:20–22), when Edom successfully broke free from Israelite control.</p>',

    "41": '<p>"Esau held a grudge against Jacob... \'then I will kill my brother Jacob\'" — Esau\'s plan echoes Cain\'s response to having his offering rejected in favor of Abel\'s: the older brother resolves to kill the younger whom YHWH (or circumstances) has preferred. The echo is not incidental — the Cain-Abel pattern of primogeniture reversal and murderous sibling jealousy is the deep narrative structure here. Esau\'s resolve to wait until Isaac\'s death (the mourning period) before acting adds a calculated, socially aware dimension to his intent.</p>',

    "42": '<p>"Rebekah was told what her older son Esau had said" — how Rebekah learned of Esau\'s plan is not specified, suggesting either a network of household informants or an informal communication system within the extended family compound. The ANE household was not a private nuclear family; it was a social unit with multiple servants, workers, and dependents, among whom information circulated. Rebekah\'s access to Esau\'s private thoughts indicates she has the household awareness necessary to act before the threat materializes.</p>',

    "43": '<p>"Flee at once to my brother Laban in Haran" — Laban, introduced in Genesis 24 as Rebekah\'s brother, is the kinship safe haven. Haran (the city of Terah\'s settlement, Gen 11:31–32) is Rebekah\'s family city. Sending Jacob to her brother\'s household places him within the kinship protection system: as a nephew of Laban, Jacob will have social standing and claim on hospitality that a stranger would not. The plan is to remove Jacob from the danger zone — Esau\'s presence — until the threat dissipates.</p>',

    "44": '<p>"Stay with him for a while until your brother\'s fury subsides" — <em>yāmîm ʾăḥāḏîm</em> (a few days, some days) is Rebekah\'s optimistic estimate; the actual period will be twenty years (Gen 31:38). The underestimation is either naïve or deliberately understated to make the plan more palatable to Jacob. Rebekah\'s calculation assumes Esau\'s anger is temporary — a normal sibling grievance that time will heal. The narrative irony is that she never sees Jacob again.</p>',

    "45": '<p>"Why should I lose both of you in one day?" — if Jacob is killed, Esau will face the blood-guilt penalty for fratricide (cf. Gen 9:6; Num 35:16–21). Rebekah calculates that losing Jacob to murder would also mean losing Esau to the consequences of murder. Her concern is both maternal (losing both sons) and strategically sound: the killing would trigger a response that would cost Esau his standing or his life. This double-loss argument gives her intervention its urgency.</p>',

    "46": '<p>"I\'m disgusted with living because of these Hittite women" — Rebekah\'s complaint to Isaac uses a legitimate grievance (Esau\'s Hittite wives, mentioned in 26:34–35) as the diplomatic pretext for sending Jacob to Paddan-Aram. The real reason (Esau\'s murder threat) is concealed. In the ANE social context, openly revealing a son\'s murderous intentions to his father would create a crisis of household governance; presenting the departure as a marriage mission allows Jacob to leave without triggering a family rupture. Rebekah is operating within the honor-shame social framework, where maintaining household face was a practical necessity.</p>',
  },
  "28": {
    "1": '<p>"So Isaac called for Jacob and blessed him" — the blessing here (vv.1–4) is Isaac\'s conscious, intentional blessing, distinct from the deceived blessing of ch.27. Isaac now knows who Jacob is and blesses him deliberately for his journey. The two blessings together — the deceived blessing of covenant headship and the knowing blessing for the mission — double-confirm that Jacob carries the covenant forward. The command "Do not marry a Canaanite woman" echoes Abraham\'s instruction to his servant in 24:3, connecting the two wife-seeking missions as parallel covenant actions.</p>',

    "2": '<p>"Go at once to Paddan Aram, to the house of your mother\'s father Bethuel. Take a wife for yourself there, from among the daughters of Laban, your mother\'s brother" — Paddan-Aram (paddān ʾărām, "the plain of Aram") is an alternative designation for the region around Haran in upper Mesopotamia, used primarily by the Priestly source. The instruction mirrors 24:4 (where Abraham sent the servant to "my country and my own relatives") but is now addressed directly to the covenant heir. Jacob will travel the same route as the servant, to the same extended family, but without a household escort — alone.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"May God Almighty bless you and make you fruitful and increase your numbers until you become a community of peoples" — <em>ʾEl-Šaddai</em> (God Almighty) is the name under which the Abrahamic covenant was formally established (17:1). Isaac\'s deliberate use of this divine name in the blessing signals that this is a formal covenant-transfer blessing, not a casual paternal wish. "Make you fruitful and increase your numbers" (<em>pĕrēh wĕrĕḇēh</em>) echoes the creation blessing of 1:28 and the specific covenant language of 17:6 — Jacob is being placed within the full trajectory of the Abrahamic covenant.</p>',

    "4": '<p>"May he give you and your descendants the blessing given to Abraham, so that you may take possession of the land where you now reside as a foreigner, the land God gave to Abraham" — the Abrahamic blessing is now explicitly named and transferred to Jacob. The phrase <em>birkat ʾAḇrāhām</em> (the blessing of Abraham) is the summary of the covenant promises: land, descendants, and the universal blessing (12:1–3). Isaac is performing a formal covenant-investiture, consciously placing Jacob within the line of promise. "The land where you now reside as a foreigner" (<em>mĕgûrêkhā</em>, your sojournings) acknowledges the provisional, not-yet-fulfilled nature of the land promise.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"So Isaac sent Jacob on his way, and he went to Paddan Aram, to Laban son of Bethuel the Aramean, the brother of Rebekah, who was the mother of Jacob and Esau" — the narrator\'s summary includes a genealogical note that emphasizes Rebekah\'s centrality: she is mother of both sons and sister of Laban, making Jacob\'s destination his mother\'s homeland. The Aramean identification of Bethuel (and by extension Laban) is consistent with the later covenant confession "a wandering Aramean was my father" (Deut 26:5) — Jacob\'s family connections to Aram are the background for that liturgical formula.</p>',

    "6": '<p>"Now Esau learned that Isaac had blessed Jacob and had sent him to Paddan Aram to take a wife from there" — the narrator shifts to Esau\'s perspective. Esau\'s observation of Isaac\'s actions toward Jacob — blessing, sending, commanding about marriage — produces a new self-awareness in Esau. He is presented here not as the murderous rival but as a son trying to understand what pleases his father. The contrast with his earlier murderous resolve (27:41) is notable; the narrative presents Esau as capable of course-correction.</p>',

    "7": '<p>"Jacob had obeyed his father and mother and had gone to Paddan Aram" — Esau observes Jacob\'s obedience. The word <em>šāmaʿ</em> (he heard/obeyed) frames Jacob\'s departure as parental compliance, not flight. Esau sees a son who does what his parents command, and implicitly recognizes that he has not measured up to this standard — his Hittite marriages (26:34–35) were a source of grief to his parents (26:35), not acts of obedience.</p>',

    "8": '<p>"Esau then realized how displeasing the Canaanite women were to his father Isaac" — the word <em>raʿ</em> (evil, displeasing) describes Isaac\'s view of Canaanite women as marriage partners. Esau\'s realization is not that the marriages were wrong in themselves but that they displeased his father — an honor-shame response, not an ethical one. The narrative presents Esau\'s motivation as relational repair (pleasing his father) rather than covenant obedience.</p>',

    "9": '<p>"He went to Ishmael and married Mahalath, the sister of Nebaioth and daughter of Ishmael son of Abraham" — Esau\'s attempted correction is to marry within Abraham\'s extended family. Ishmael was Abraham\'s son by Hagar; Ishmael\'s daughter is therefore Abraham\'s granddaughter and Esau\'s first cousin once removed. The choice is genealogically closer to the covenant family than the Hittite women, but Ishmael represents the excluded line (17:18–21: the covenant runs through Isaac, not Ishmael). Esau\'s marriage is a half-measure: it addresses the family connection criterion while missing the covenant line distinction.</p>',

    "10": '<p>"Jacob left Beersheba and set out for Haran" — Beersheba, the southernmost settlement in the promised land, is the departure point. The journey from Beersheba to Haran was approximately 450–500 miles through varied terrain. Jacob travels alone, carrying nothing the narrative specifies — a contrast with the well-equipped caravan of ten camels sent for Rebekah in ch.24. The solitude of Jacob\'s journey is the context for the Bethel theophany: stripped of family protection and material resources, Jacob is in a position to receive a direct divine encounter.</p>',

    "11": '<p>"When he reached a certain place, he stopped for the night because the sun had set. Taking one of the stones there, he put it under his head and lay down to sleep" — the "certain place" (<em>hammāqôm</em>) is later identified as Bethel (v.19). The Hebrew term <em>māqôm</em> (place) acquires a sacred valence in Genesis — it often designates a location of divine encounter (cf. 12:6; 22:4). Sleeping with a stone as a headrest was common in the ancient Near East; hard surfaces were standard for travelers without bedding, and the stone served as a raised support for the head. The detail is realistic, not symbolic — until the stone itself becomes the subject of consecration in v.18.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"He had a dream in which he saw a stairway resting on the earth, with its top reaching to heaven, and the angels of God were ascending and descending on it" — the Hebrew <em>sullām</em> (stairway/ramp) appears only here in the OT. The Akkadian <em>simmiltu</em> (ladder, ramp) is a cognate associated with the ramps of ziggurats — the ANE\'s monumental structures conceived as stairways connecting earth and heaven. The ANE audience would have recognized the imagery: a divine ramp between the cosmic realms, with divine messengers (<em>malʾākîm</em>) moving between them. The angels ascending before descending suggests they were already present on earth — YHWH\'s messengers are not distant from the earthly realm.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"There above it stood the LORD" — the divine position "above" (<em>mēʿālāyw</em>) the stairway is the throne-room positioning: YHWH at the apex of the cosmic structure, the source from which the communication descends. What follows is the formal covenant declaration, using the self-identification formula of covenant inauguration: "I am the LORD, the God of your father Abraham and the God of Isaac." This formula echoes the Exodus self-identification (Exod 6:3) and places the Bethel theophany within the same covenant trajectory. The promise of the land is renewed in the specific terms of the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 12:7; 13:15).</p>',

    "14": '<p>"Your descendants will be like the dust of the earth, and you will spread out to the west and to the east, to the north and to the south. All peoples on earth will be blessed through you and your offspring" — the covenant promise is renewed in its full four-directional scope. The dust-of-the-earth simile for innumerability echoes 13:16 (Abraham\'s promise). The four-direction spread (west, east, north, south) is the complete geographical formula. "All peoples on earth will be blessed through you and your offspring" directly quotes the universal dimension of the Abrahamic covenant (12:3; 22:18), now explicitly transferred to Jacob.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"I am with you and will watch over you wherever you go, and I will bring you back to this land. I will not leave you until I have done what I have promised you" — the divine presence promise (<em>ʾānōkhî ʿimmākh</em>, I am with you) is the covenant\'s personal dimension. Jacob is departing from the promised land — and YHWH promises to accompany him into exile and return him. The phrase "I will not leave you until I have done what I have promised" is the guarantee of covenant faithfulness: the promise is not contingent on Jacob\'s faithfulness but on YHWH\'s. This covenant format — unconditional divine commitment — mirrors the Abrahamic covenant\'s unconditional character (15:17–21).</p>',

    "16": '<p>"Surely the LORD is in this place, and I was not aware of it" — Jacob\'s awakening brings the recognition formula: <em>ʾākēn yēš YHWH bammāqôm hazzeh wĕʾānōkhî lōʾ yāḏaʿtî</em> (Surely YHWH is in this place and I did not know). The statement reflects the ANE understanding that divine presence was attached to specific locations — not that YHWH was everywhere, but that particular places were nodes of divine presence. Jacob\'s surprise ("I was not aware of it") suggests he was not traveling to a known sacred site; the encounter is unilaterally initiated by YHWH.</p>',

    "17": '<p>"How awesome is this place! This is none other than the house of God; this is the gate of heaven" — <em>bêt ʾĕlōhîm</em> (house of God) and <em>šaʿar haššāmāyim</em> (gate of heaven) are Jacob\'s interpretive naming of what he has seen. In ANE cosmology, the "gate of heaven" is the point of divine-human intersection — the place where communication between the divine realm and the earthly realm is possible. The Babylonian term for a sacred city was <em>bāb-ilī</em> (gate of God/Babel), sharing the same theological concept. Jacob has stumbled onto a cosmic threshold without knowing it.</p>',

    "18": '<p>"Jacob took the stone he had placed under his head and set it up as a pillar and poured oil on top of it" — the stone becomes a <em>maṣṣēḇāh</em> (standing stone, pillar), the standard form of a sacred marker in the Canaanite world and in early Israelite practice. Setting up a standing stone consecrated the location as a sacred site; pouring oil on it (<em>wayyiṣṣōq šemen ʿal-rōʾšāh</em>) was the act of anointing that transferred the stone from the profane to the sacred category. The later Mosaic law prohibited standing stones (Lev 26:1; Deut 16:22) in the context of Canaanite cultic practice; Jacob\'s pre-Mosaic pillar exists before that prohibition and is not condemned.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"He called that place Bethel, though the city used to be called Luz" — <em>Bêt-ʾĒl</em> (house of God) is Jacob\'s naming of the site, derived directly from his proclamation in v.17. The city of Luz is mentioned in Josh 16:2 and Judg 1:26 as the pre-Israelite name of the settlement. Bethel will become one of the most significant cultic sites in the OT: the location of Abraham\'s altar (12:8), Jacob\'s vow site (35:1–15), and later the northern kingdom\'s official cult center under Jeroboam (1 Kgs 12:28–29). Its history spans both faithful and unfaithful uses.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"Then Jacob made a vow, saying, \'If God will be with me and will watch over me on this journey I am taking and will give me food to eat and clothes to wear\'" — a <em>neder</em> (vow) in the ANE was a conditional promise to a deity: "if you do X, I will do Y." The conditions Jacob names (divine presence, safe journey, food, clothing) correspond closely to what YHWH has just promised (v.15: "I am with you and will watch over you wherever you go"). Jacob is not imposing conditions on YHWH but expressing his acceptance of the covenant terms using the formal ANE vow structure.</p>',

    "21": '<p>"So that I return safely to my father\'s household, then the LORD will be my God" — the "if... then" structure of Jacob\'s vow is the standard conditional vow form. "The LORD will be my God" is not a conditional that Jacob imposes — it echoes the covenant formula ("I will be your God") back in the direction of human acceptance. The covenant relationship requires both parties; Jacob\'s vow expresses his side of the covenant commitment in response to YHWH\'s unconditional declaration of vv.13–15. The vow is an act of faith, not bargaining.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"This stone that I have set up as a pillar will be God\'s house, and of all that you give me I will give you a tenth" — two commitments close the vow: the pillar will become a sacred site (a permanent memorial of the encounter), and Jacob commits to giving a tithe (<em>ʿāśēr ʾăʿaśrennû lākh</em>, I will certainly give a tenth to you) from all he receives. The tithe commitment is the second instance of tithing in Genesis (the first being Abraham\'s gift to Melchizedek in 14:20); it establishes a pattern of returning a portion of covenant prosperity to the covenant God. The tithe is not presented as an obligation but as a voluntary act of covenant loyalty.</p>',
  }
}

